    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-07-23T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-07-23T17:00:00-05:00" n="1078"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1078">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">760h.68/7–2645: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 1078<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_KA1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d1078fn1">A report on the British representations described
                        in this message was included in telegram No. 113 of July 24 from <persName
                            corresp="#p_GJC1">Grew</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_BJF1"
                            >Byrnes</persName> (file No. 800.00 Summaries/7–2445).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caserta</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-07-24T00:00:00+02:00"
                            >July 24, 1945—midnight</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3047. When we were in Belgrade on July 18 British Ambassador<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d1078fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_SRCS1">R. C. Skrine Stevenson</persName>.</note> at
                    dinner with <persName corresp="#p_SH3">Shantz</persName> informed us that he had
                    been instructed by <gloss target="#t_ForOff1">ForOff</gloss> to make strong
                    representations to Yugo Govt with regard to propaganda of Belgrade radio, Yugo
                    press and “inflammatory statements of responsible Yugo statesmen” on questions
                    of Greek Yugo frontier and Venezia Giulia. <persName corresp="#p_SRCS1"
                        >Stevenson</persName> stated he had been instructed to seek an audience with
                        <persName corresp="#p_TMJB1">Marshal Tito</persName> on Axis [<hi
                        rend="italic">this</hi>] subject.</p>
                <p>We have just seen two telegrams from British Ambassador Belgrade to <gloss
                        target="#t_FonOffs1">FonOff</gloss> reporting <persName corresp="#p_SRCS1"
                        >Stevenson</persName>’s conversations with <persName corresp="#p_TMJB1"
                        >Tito</persName> on this subject. After having heard <persName
                        corresp="#p_SRCS1">Stevenson</persName>’s complaints, <persName
                        corresp="#p_TMJB1">Tito</persName> replied that insofar as his personal
                    declarations were concerned he felt that he was obliged to keep Yugo people
                    informed as to developments in international position of Yugo. He added that
                    Yugo propaganda in regard to Greek Yugo frontier was in retaliation to
                    inflammatory attacks of Greek radio and press against Yugo. <persName
                        corresp="#p_TMJB1">Tito</persName> went on to say that insofar as Yugo
                    propaganda campaign re Venezia Giulia was involved British press was largely to
                    blame and cited specifically articles in “<hi rend="italic">Nineteenth
                        Century</hi>” [and] “<hi rend="italic">Time and Tide</hi>”.</p>
                <p>British Ambassador stated he could not accept this argument and suggested that it
                    would be most desirable if Yugo Govt should settle any difficulties with Greek
                    Govt by direct negotiation.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_TMJB1">Tito</persName> agreed to this suggestion and said
                    he was ready to proceed at once with conversations to this end.</p>
                <p>British Ambassador’s message on this subject concluded with statement that he was
                    not optimistic that Yugo press would change its present line.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
